node.text:
600k 🥺💛 THANK YOU!
⠀
5 years ago (July 2016) I quit my 9-5 and I took photography and blogging full time. Never in my wildest dreams would I have expected that endeavor to turn into what it is today. I have the immense privilege of bringing beautiful places right to your fingertips, and teaching travel + outdoor tips so that you can take similar adventures. I pinch myself every day that this is my job… and I have you to thank for that!
⠀
Every time you like one of my photos, leave a comment, share with friends, watch my Stories, read a blog post, gift @roamingamericabook, or purchase something I link… that really helps and it does not go unnoticed. I seriously have the BEST followers and I appreciate your ongoing support! 🙌🏼
⠀
📍@panoramaglasslodge, Iceland. One of the most insane sunrises I’ve ever seen! 🔥

node.text:
Would you try out van life? 🚐🏔
⠀
A few years ago @matthewhahnel and I lived out of various vehicles for about 18 months (a camper like this one, our Toyota 4Runner, rental cars, and rental vans). It was some of the best times of our lives but also some of the most stressful. The best parts were freedom to wake up in amazing places and being able to spend so much time outdoors. The biggest downsides were constantly worrying about where we would sleep, use the bathroom, and shower. Pros and cons!
⠀
These days we love having a house as our home base and we enjoy taking 2-3 week long road trips or quick weekend adventures. It’s the perfect combination of home life and road life for us!
⠀
Also want to fully acknowledge the privilege of being about to choose whether or not to live out of a vehicle. For many people it’s a necessity for survival and I’m thankful to have been able to experience the positive aspects of road life.
⠀
📍Coast Salish and Wenatchi lands
⠀
Camper rental ⤳ @peacevans (a very similar VW Westfalia Vanagon to ‘Ruby’ from our 2017 national parks trip ☺️)

node.text:
Mini tour of my solo car camping set up for sleeping in my SUV🌲
⠀
Click the link in my bio for a “Car Camping Basics” guide, where I’m sharing all my camping essentials and tips!
⠀
This blog post is in collaboration with my go-to outdoor retailer, @Backcountry. They have tons of amazing car camping gear, plus fast shipping options and helpful staff ready to give advice. Use code RENEE15 to get 15% off your entire first Backcountry order (some exclusions apply) 🙌🏼
⠀
Items featured in the video (direct links can be found in my “car camping” story highlight!)👇🏼
▫️Stoic Single Cloud Camp Bed
▫️Pendleton Wool Blankets
▫️Stoic Basecamp Bivy Quilt
▫️Yeti Tundra 35 Hard Cooler
▫️Stanley Water Jug
▫️Inergy Power Box
▫️Minetom Twinkle Lights
▫️Goal Zero Lantern
▫️Weather Tech Window Shades
▫️Qualizzi Window Bug Covers
▫️Bear Spray
▫️Coleman Camp Stove
▫️Stoic Fireside Five O’Clock Chair
▫️Stoic Feather Lite Table
⠀
Frequently asked question 👉🏼 My vehicle is a 2008 Toyota 4Runner and the back seats are partially removed + folded down. I don’t have a bed platform and my sleeping gear is sitting straight on top of the flooring.
⠀
AD #FindYourBackcountry

node.accessibility_caption: Woman standing in front of lava flow in Iceland

node.text:
Would you stand near a river of lava? (swipe to see the video)🔥🌋 Being next to the lava was HOT… in fact, at one point I thought I had burned my face from looking at it too much haha. But then we got further up the mountain to the volcano viewpoint and it was FREEEEEZING cold. I think the photo of @maria_sheldon and I all bundled up shows exactly how cold yet ecstatic we were 😆
⠀
Photos captured by @KyleKotajarvi
⠀
Click the link in my bio for my Iceland guide and in-depth road trip itinerary!

node.accessibility_caption: Two women standing in front of erupting volcano in Iceland
Man and woman standing in front of active volcano lava flow in Iceland
Woman relaxing in tent with Mount Baker behind a wildflowers around. Located in Washington State

node.text:
Winter in Washington can feel long, but summer nights in the mountains are always worth the wait ⛺️☀️🌸🥾🏔
⠀
Disclaimer: My tent is in a camping spot and not along the trail. This is a side trail to the campsite and the camera angle makes it difficult to see everything. Please always follow Leave No Trace when backpacking and don’t trample wildflowers.
⠀
📍Coast Salish, Nooksack, and Nlaka’pamux lands

node.text:
First time paddling in a see-through kayak! It was so amazing to watch the rocks and fish pass below us ☀️🐟
⠀
Kayak rental from @the.wild.society in Lake Tahoe
⠀
📍 Washoe lands
